{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency if and only if (net majorities correctly saved from false rejection) > (net majorities incorrectly broken by false flags). Formally: R*(1 - P_NF) * P_flip_correct > (1 - R)*P_NF*P_break_correct, where R=critic recall on wrong candidates, P=critic precision, P_NF=prob critic flags the pool, and P_flip_correct is the probability the remaining pool, after removing true-positive flags, now yields the right answer.\", \"mechanism\": \"Two competing causal channels operate on the SAME k-candidate pool: (1) the rescue channel—critic flags genuinely wrong candidates, removing them so a previously-fragmented majority coalesces on the correct answer; (2) the erosion channel—critic false-flags correct candidates, breaking a correct majority and letting a wrong answer win. The harness strictly beats SC when the rescue flux exceeds the erosion flux. The observed v4-pro hard-set (recall=1.0, precision=0.125, net=0) is the equilibrium where these fluxes exactly cancel; the v4-flash easy-set (all arms 0.958) is the trivial regime where base error is too low for rescue to matter (P_NF ≈ 0). The decisive variable is critic precision as a function of pool difficulty: precision collapses on hard items because the critic itself struggles, producing the false-flag erosion that kills the harness.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k in [5, 15]\", \"base candidate error e in (1/(k+1), 1/2)\", \"critic precision and recall both strictly in (0, 1)\", \"binary-answer QA tasks\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"e <= 1/(k+1) (majority always correct, no rescue possible)\", \"e >= 1/2 (majority always wrong, harness cannot manufacture correctness from a wrong pool)\", \"perfect-precision critic (trivially dominates)\", \"continuous-generation tasks without discrete majority semantics\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment yields a mid-zone arm (1/(k+1) < e < 1/2) where harness recall >= 0.5 AND precision >= 0.6 AND harness accuracy <= SC accuracy across ALL tested k in {7, 9, 11}\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Across all tested difficulty bins, measured (rescue flux - erosion flux) has the wrong sign relative to (harness accuracy - SC accuracy), i.e. flux model predicts harness win but SC wins or ties in 4+ of 6 bins\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"The flux-balance equation subsumes the neighbourhood's fragility-window claim (7811dbda, 2d711b2e): the window 1/(k+1) < e < 1/2 is the necessary condition for P_flip_correct > 0, but it is not sufficient—precision must also be high enough that the erosion channel does not cancel rescue. The refuted candidate (133fcf5d) likely claimed a fixed-precision/recall sufficiency without the flux inequality; the present claim adds the causal flux mechanism and the precision-vs-difficulty collapse explanation for why the observed hard-set netted to zero.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"},{"role":"dependence","target":"2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"},{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"mention","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"}],"typicality":0.92},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"No single critic fixed at one precision/recall operating point can strictly beat self-consistency across a realistic difficulty distribution; the harness strictly wins only when the critic's precision is adaptively boosted on exactly the mid-zone items where the majority is fragile, via question-conditioned (difficulty-adaptive) critic gating that suppresses flags on easy and very-hard items.\", \"mechanism\": \"A fixed-operating-point critic faces an inescapable precision-difficulty tradeoff: on easy items (low e) any flag is likely a false flag (precision -> 0, observed v4-flash easy: precision=0.333), and on hard items the critic's own error rate inflates false flags (observed v4-pro hard: precision=0.125). The erosion channel thus dominates at both tails of the difficulty distribution. Only a critic that can condition its flagging threshold on an estimate of pool difficulty—suppressing flags when confidence is low—can concentrate its true-positive flags on the mid-zone where rescue is both possible and needed. The causal mechanism is selection-on-difficulty: adaptive gating shifts the critic's operating point along its precision-recall curve, raising precision in the mid-zone at the cost of recall on tails where recall is worthless anyway.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k >= 5 odd\", \"base error e in (1/(k+1), 1/2) for at least a subset of items\", \"critic with access to a difficulty signal (logit margin, self-uncertainty, or pool entropy)\", \"binary QA\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"fixed-threshold critic without difficulty conditioning (per refuted 133fcf5d and base-case 55975070)\", \"e uniformly outside the fragility window\", \"critic with perfect oracle difficulty estimation (trivial)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Adaptive-gated critic achieves harness accuracy > SC accuracy on mid-zone items but the SAME adaptive-gated critic also beats SC on >= 80% of items outside the fragility window, which would contradict the necessity of the fragility regime\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"No difficulty bin in the experiment shows a statistically significant harness > SC gap (binomial p > 0.05) despite adaptive gating and mid-zone base error, refuting the sufficiency of adaptive precision boosting\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate aligns with 30e483eb's emphasis on question-adaptive critic confidence. It predicts the refuted candidate (133fcf5d) failed precisely because it assumed a fixed critic. The decisive experiment must use a difficulty-stratified design so that each bin has enough items for a binomial test, not just aggregate accuracy. Token budget: ~210k, leaving margin for a replication fold.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"mention","target":"7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}],"typicality":0.80},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"For any finite pool of k candidates, the harness-filtered majority vote can NEVER strictly beat self-consistency on the SAME pool when the critic operates on candidate-answer strings alone (no privileged answer-key or gold feedback), because the critic's error is confounded with the candidate's error: the candidates most likely to produce a wrong-majority pool are exactly the ones for which the critic is also most likely to err, so erosion always cancels rescue in expectation.\", \"mechanism\": \"Under a model where the critic M_c is a peer of the candidate generator M_g with correlated errors (both draw from the same model family / training data), there exists a shared latent difficulty variable D such that high-D items simultaneously increase candidate base error AND critic false-flag rate. On high-D items (where rescue is needed because the majority is fragile), critic precision collapses (as observed: precision=0.125 on hard-set). On low-D items (where precision is higher), the majority is already robust so rescue is unnecessary. This creates an anti-correlation between the value of intervention and the quality of intervention, making strict harness > SC impossible in expectation with a single peer critic. The only escape is to decorrelate critic error from candidate error, e.g., by using a critic from a different model family with orthogonal failure modes, which is outside the stated single-provider setup.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k=5 single-provider studies where the critic is the same model family as the candidate generator\", \"critic sees only candidate answers, no gold label\", \"binary QA\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"cross-family critic (e.g., GPT-class critic on Llama-class candidates)\", \"critic with access to external verification tools (code execution, retrieval)\", \"human-in-the-loop critic\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"The peer-critic arm achieves harness accuracy strictly greater than SC accuracy (binomial p < 0.05, one-sided) in ANY difficulty bin or k condition, which would refute the impossibility claim for the single-peer-critic regime\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The cross-family critic arm achieves harness accuracy <= SC accuracy in the mid-zone bin despite having measured precision > 0.5 and recall > 0.5, which would refute the claim that decorrelation is the necessary escape\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the skeptical atypical candidate: it asserts the refuted 133fcf5d was not wrong about the regime but wrong about the possibility—strict dominance is impossible within a single provider's model family because of error correlation. The neighbourhood's 30e483eb (adaptive confidence) is a partial escape but only if the adaptation can break the correlation, which a peer model cannot reliably do. The experiment includes a cross-family critic arm as a contrast: if the cross-family arm wins in the mid-zone while the peer arm does not, the claim is confirmed. Token budget: ~225k.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"74fde5320d6c79520ea82d22a3e0c25a5ecc8e0cb50c3197058c5a3b0ecd2845"},{"role":"mention","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"mention","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}],"typicality":0.22}]}